. Acuña. Host: 
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF2FF9BFF71FE0CFE7B56DB" authorityName="Montenegro &amp; Aguilera" authorityYear="2018" box="[192,438,420,446]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Homoeomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis id="B977EAD4FFF2FF9BFF71FE0CFE7B56DB" box="[192,438,420,446]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Homoeomma chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Montenegro &amp; Aguilera (
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF2FF9BFD64FE0DFC4D56DA" box="[725,896,420,447]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Theraphosidae</taxonomicName>
), adult or subadult female. The wasp dragged the paralyzed tarantula backwards across the ground and through low vegetation, dorsal side upward, grasping the base of its second left leg with her mandibles (
<bibRefCitation id="EF924B37FFF2FF9BFD0EFE40FC875566" author="Acuna ST" box="[703,842,489,515]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" refId="ref20763" refString="Acuna ST. 2021. Avispa mata tarantulas. Available at https: // www. instagram. com / p / CU 7 jwRZg 5 hK /. (Last accessed 14 November 2021)." type="url" year="2021">Acuña 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
